## `test_posix_same_process_upgrades()`
<!-- checksum: placeholder-locks-6 -->

### Purpose
A process that already holds a shared lock can upgrade to exclusive via another `posix_lock` call — no conflict with itself.

### Postconditions

```python
lm = LockManager()
lm.posix_lock(inode=1, fd_id=10, pid=1000, op="shared", start=0, length=0)
lm.posix_lock(inode=1, fd_id=10, pid=1000, op="exclusive", start=0, length=0)
q = lm.posix_getlk(inode=1, fd_id=10, pid=1000, start=0, length=0)
assert q.type == "exclusive"
```

---

## `test_posix_range_lock_non_overlapping()`
<!-- checksum: placeholder-locks-7 -->

### Purpose
Two processes can hold exclusive locks on non-overlapping byte ranges.

### Postconditions

```python
lm = LockManager()
lm.posix_lock(inode=1, fd_id=10, pid=1000, op="exclusive", start=0, length=100)
# Different pid on a disjoint range: OK.
lm.posix_lock(inode=1, fd_id=20, pid=2000, op="exclusive", start=100, length=100)
```

---

## `test_posix_length_zero_means_infinity()`
<!-- checksum: placeholder-locks-8 -->

### Purpose
Per POSIX, `length=0` means "from `start` to EOF / infinity". A zero-length lock at offset 0 covers every future byte.

### Postconditions

```python
lm = LockManager()
lm.posix_lock(inode=1, fd_id=10, pid=1000, op="exclusive", start=0, length=0)
# Any byte range conflicts — here we pick bytes near 2^62 to prove infinity.
with pytest.raises(LockConflict):
    lm.posix_lock(inode=1, fd_id=20, pid=2000, op="shared",
                  start=(1 << 62), length=100)
```

---

## `test_posix_close_any_fd_releases_all()`
<!-- checksum: placeholder-locks-9 -->

### Purpose
POSIX's "broken" semantic: closing *any* fd for the inode in that process releases *all* POSIX locks that process holds on the inode. This is the bug POSIX baked into the API and OFD locks were introduced to fix.

### Postconditions

```python
lm = LockManager()
lm.posix_lock(inode=1, fd_id=10, pid=1000, op="exclusive", start=0, length=100)
lm.posix_lock(inode=1, fd_id=10, pid=1000, op="exclusive", start=200, length=100)
# Close a DIFFERENT fd for the same (inode, pid) — releases both.
lm.on_fd_close(inode=1, fd_id=999, pid=1000)

# Another process can now acquire both ranges.
lm.posix_lock(inode=1, fd_id=20, pid=2000, op="exclusive", start=0, length=100)
lm.posix_lock(inode=1, fd_id=20, pid=2000, op="exclusive", start=200, length=100)
```

---

## `test_posix_unlock_releases_range()`
<!-- checksum: placeholder-locks-10 -->

### Postconditions

```python
lm = LockManager()
lm.posix_lock(inode=1, fd_id=10, pid=1000, op="exclusive", start=0, length=100)
lm.posix_lock(inode=1, fd_id=10, pid=1000, op="unlock", start=0, length=100)
# Another process can now acquire it.
lm.posix_lock(inode=1, fd_id=20, pid=2000, op="exclusive", start=0, length=100)
```

