## `test_ofd_scoped_by_fd_not_pid()`
<!-- checksum: placeholder-locks-11 -->

### Purpose
OFD locks are scoped by open-file-description (fd), not by process. Same pid holding two fds behaves like two separate lock owners.

### Postconditions

```python
lm = LockManager()
lm.ofd_lock(inode=1, fd_id=10, op="exclusive", start=0, length=100)
# Same pid, different fd — conflicts because OFD scopes on fd, not pid.
with pytest.raises(LockConflict):
    lm.ofd_lock(inode=1, fd_id=11, op="exclusive", start=0, length=100)
```

---

## `test_ofd_close_releases_only_its_locks()`
<!-- checksum: placeholder-locks-12 -->

### Purpose
Unlike POSIX, closing fd 10 only releases fd 10's OFD locks. fd 11's locks remain.

### Postconditions

```python
lm = LockManager()
lm.ofd_lock(inode=1, fd_id=10, op="exclusive", start=0, length=100)
lm.ofd_lock(inode=1, fd_id=11, op="exclusive", start=200, length=100)
lm.on_fd_close(inode=1, fd_id=10, pid=1000)

# fd 10's range is free; fd 11's range is still locked.
lm.ofd_lock(inode=1, fd_id=20, op="exclusive", start=0, length=100)
with pytest.raises(LockConflict):
    lm.ofd_lock(inode=1, fd_id=21, op="exclusive", start=200, length=100)
```

---

## `test_flock_whole_file_only()`
<!-- checksum: placeholder-locks-13 -->

### Purpose
BSD `flock` takes no range; it always applies to the whole file. The API does not accept `start`/`length` parameters.

### Postconditions

```python
lm = LockManager()
lm.flock(inode=1, fd_id=10, op="exclusive")
# Another fd cannot acquire any lock on any range via flock.
with pytest.raises(LockConflict):
    lm.flock(inode=1, fd_id=11, op="exclusive")
with pytest.raises(LockConflict):
    lm.flock(inode=1, fd_id=11, op="shared")
```

---

