## `test_posix_and_flock_are_separate_namespaces()`
<!-- checksum: placeholder-locks-15 -->

### Purpose
Per Linux kernel: POSIX advisory locks and BSD `flock` are entirely separate namespaces. A POSIX exclusive lock does not prevent a `flock` exclusive lock, and vice versa. (OFD vs flock: same — separate namespaces.)

### Postconditions

```python
lm = LockManager()
lm.posix_lock(inode=1, fd_id=10, pid=1000, op="exclusive", start=0, length=0)
# flock exclusive: no conflict because different namespace.
lm.flock(inode=1, fd_id=20, op="exclusive")
# ofd exclusive: also different namespace.
lm.ofd_lock(inode=1, fd_id=30, op="exclusive", start=0, length=0)
```

---

## `test_wait_false_raises_immediately()`
<!-- checksum: placeholder-locks-16 -->

### Purpose
`wait=False` is the non-blocking variant (`F_SETLK`, `LOCK_NB`). Conflict raises `LockConflict` without blocking.

### Postconditions

```python
lm = LockManager()
lm.posix_lock(inode=1, fd_id=10, pid=1000, op="exclusive", start=0, length=0)
with pytest.raises(LockConflict):
    lm.posix_lock(inode=1, fd_id=20, pid=2000, op="exclusive",
                  start=0, length=0, wait=False)
```

